post_text: Our hallways and classrooms are buzzing with excitement. Welcome back students.
text: Our hallways and classrooms are buzzing with excitement. Welcome back students.

post_text:
Welcome to the 2020-21 school year. So many new opportunities, unknown challenges and excitement awaits. Whether students are attending as a distance learner or in the traditional classroom, we are excited to begin the year.

Thank you to the MCS team members who have worked diligently to ensure that our schools are ready to open and our students have an amazing re-entry to school.

As we begin this unconventional year, we especially thank our community and parents for your patience and flexibility.

We miss our friend and leader - Dr Linda Gilbert - but we think she would be proud.

WOW! Sometimes we just need to pat ourselves on the back and give huge shout outs to our nutrition team, SROs, transportation, outreach, City Schools Foundation, city officials, community partners and so many others.

Today was the last day for our CHOW bus for summer meals. 154,554 meals have been served plus 17,698 weekend food bags have been distributed since March 16.

This was an all-hands-on-deck success. Our team rose to the challenge.

This week, our SROs conducted training with the Travis Manion Foundation. The training was designed to reinforce the concepts and principles of the Character Does Matter Program. The program touches 24 character strengths that are important for students to use not only while in school, but to develop their character that they may carry those traits with them as adults, parents, and professionals.

United Way of Rutherford and Cannon Counties
June 8 at 8:02 AM ·

This year's Literacy Day of Action will be dedicated to Dr. Linda Gilbert, who was Director of Murfreesboro City Schools and a tireless advocate for children's education. We commemorate her lifetime of service to students' well-being, and we are proud to have worked side by side with her for many years to help improve the lives of children and families in our community. She will be deeply missed.

Now through June 16, United Way is hosting a drive to collect new or gently used books and other educational resources that children need during the summer months to help prevent “summer slide” – especially since schools have been closed during the pandemic!

For more information, visit https://www.yourlocaluw.org/literacydayofaction.

The collected items will be distributed to neighbors in need via Murfreesboro City Schools’ Books on a Bus (BOB), Chow Bus and Rutherford County Schools YMCA after school program.

Thank you to our sponsors: Publix, Nissan, MYP, Regions Bank, Wilson Bank & Trust, Franklin Synergy Bank, Cornerstone Financial Credit Union, and Ingram Content Group.

post_text:
We are heartbroken to announce that our friend, mentor and boss, Dr. Linda Gilbert, passed away earlier this afternoon. Dr. Gilbert has served Murfreesboro City Schools and the community with compassion and fervor for many years. She was a dedicated mother, grandmother and educator and will be truly missed.

Dr. Gilbert received numerous awards throughout her teaching career including the Tennessee Teacher of the Year and Tennessee Superintendent of the Year. However, the awards did not define her. She was defined by the passion for her family, her church, and the children and staff of Murfreesboro City Schools.

Please keep the Gilbert and MCS families in your prayers.

Our "Stop the Summer Slide: Literacy Day of Action" is back, and we need your help!

From May 18 - June 12, United Way is hosting a drive to collect new or gently used books and other educational resources that children need during the summer months to help prevent “summer slide.”

Get all the details at https://www.yourlocaluw.org/literacydayofaction

The collected items will be distributed to neighbors in need via Murfreesboro City Schools’ Books on a Bus (BOB) and the Chow Bus.

You can get involved by purchasing items from our Amazon Wishlist to be shipped to the United Way office by June 12, donating your “gently used” books, signing up to serve as a collection site, or sharing on social media.

Visit yourlocaluw.org/literacydayofaction for a list of items needed, along with additional details about donation drop-off, "summer slide," our early education Bold Goal, and more!

Thank you to our sponsors: Nissan, MYP, Regions Bank, Wilson Bank & Trust, and Franklin Synergy Bank.

It's #WonderWednesdayTN! Have you heard of the term biomimicry? Don't worry- most people haven't! Biomimicry means designing something to imitate things found in nature. Today, engineers and designers all over the world study plants, animals, and habitats to solve problems by observing and mimicking what they see.

In today's challenge, Tennessee STEM Innovation Network encourages students to get outside and explore! Visit https://www.tsin.org/-wonderwednesdaytn to get started.

shared_text:
Scales Elementary School - Murfreesboro, TN
May 11 at 6:50 PM ·

We would like to give a huge congratulations to our fabulous Teachers of the Year, Mrs. Hix and Mrs. Pozo. These ladies are so deserving of this honor!

Mrs. Hix has been teaching for five years. She has taught third grade for her entire career so far, and thoroughly enjoys the learning and growth that happens during a student’s third grade school year. Her favorite part about teaching is forming a community within her classroom to support and champion each student. She also enjoys collaborating with fellow educators to create engaging lessons.

Mrs. Pozo has been teaching for 20 years. She taught Kindergarten through 8th grade and 12th grade English in bilingual and ESL classes. She loves it when she sees her students come out of their silent period and begin communicating in English with their peers and participating class! She loves to see their eyes light up when English begins to make sense to them!

Rana Dajani reading Jasmine and the Monster (in Arabic)

Read To Succeed
May 7 at 11:00 AM ·

Did you know that Read To Succeed often needs help translating material into Arabic? It's true, Rutherford County has a large population of residents that speak Arabic which means many of our ESL learners do too!

It's a real treat to have Rana Dajani, Family Engagement Liaison with Murfreesboro City Schools read (in Arabic) "Jasmine and the Monster"

Enjoy! https://youtu.be/ATL2kqQoM7w

And don't forget, there's still time to donate to RTS and other local nonprofits during #TheBigPayback by visiting www.thebigpayback.org/readtosucceed

Your donation helps us provide books for ESL students and continue to offer free ESL lessons to anyone living or working in Rutherford County.

#LiteracyMatters

Rana Dajani reading Jasmine and the Monster (in Arabic)

Read To Succeed
May 7 at 11:00 AM ·

Did you know that Read To Succeed often needs help translating material into Arabic? It's true, Rutherford County has a large population of residents that speak Arabic which means many of our ESL learners do too!

It's a real treat to have Rana Dajani, Family Engagement Liaison with Murfreesboro City Schools read (in Arabic) "Jasmine and the Monster"

Enjoy! https://youtu.be/ATL2kqQoM7w

And don't forget, there's still time to donate to RTS and other local nonprofits during #TheBigPayback by visiting www.thebigpayback.org/readtosucceed

Your donation helps us provide books for ESL students and continue to offer free ESL lessons to anyone living or working in Rutherford County.

#LiteracyMatters
#RuCoReads

Kindergarten registration for Murfreesboro City Schools begins Thursday, May 7 and will be open through May 15 for students entering kindergarten for the 2020-21 school year.

Families of incoming kindergartners have choices of online registration or paper applications. Visit cityschools.net for easy online registration instructions or paper applications can be found outside each school in a learning bin labeled “Kindergarten Registration”.

Early registration allows schools to prepare for the upcoming school year. It also allows families to receive resources and updates throughout the summer.

All children entering kindergarten must be five years old on or before August 15, 2020.

http://www.cityschools.net/student-info/registration/kindergarten-registration

It's #WonderWednesdayTN! Have you heard of Nanotechnology? It's today's activity, students will learn the exciting emerging field of research with applications in all STEM disciplines including the physical, chemical, life, earth and environmental sciences. By making small changes, nanotechnology scientists can create and discover new materials that have exciting new qualities—some of these materials might even make you think of favorite science fiction or comic book characters!

Visit https://www.tsin.org/-wonderwednesdaytn for the full activity.

Bradley Academy and Erma Siegel Elementary have been named Tennessee Designated STEM Schools by the Tennessee Department of Education in partnership with the Tennessee STEM Innovation Network. Only 22 schools received this 5 year designation this year.

STEM designated schools integrate STEM curriculum with project-based learning across all subject areas and programs both inside and outside the classroom.

This is the fourth STEM designation received by Murfreesboro City Schools including Overall Creek in 2018 and Discovery School in 2019.

Tennessee STEM Innovation Network
Tennessee Department of Education

post_text: Congratulations Cha'Miyah on being chosen for the all-state honor choir.
shared_text:
Mitchell-Neilson Schools
April 15 at 1:51 PM ·

A HUGE congratulations to MNS Leader, Cha’Miyah Webb!!! She was selected for the 2020 TN Treble Honor Choir- an all-state honor choir composed of the top 5th and 6th grade voices in the state of TN. She auditioned back in October and was notified in December that she was selected for this prestigious choir. Out of hundreds of auditions, 125 5th and 6th graders were selected for TN Treble Honor Choir. The TN Treble Honor Choir event was supposed to take place this Friday and Saturday, but it is part of the TN Music Educators Association Professional Development conference, and the conference, as well as all all-state ensembles were cancelled due to COVID-19. Cha’Miyah goes above and beyond in every area of academics, and we are very proud of her for being selected for this prestigious all-state choir. ￼#LeadOn￼

Science, Math or Magic? Join Mr. Knitter and Mr. Ridgley at 9:30 a.m. today live on City TV for a quick lesson on clouds and see if they can make it rain inside City Hall. It's our first live broadcast...no pressure. :).

Our students and staff have been busy this week. From optional challenges to serving meals... MCS does not stop! Over 3,900 students have been on Lexia and iReady (iReady pass rate is 88%), there were over 330 participants in the K-2 Math Challenge, over 140 participants in the 3-5 reading challenge, roughly 5,000 meals served, and lots of school supplies and books given out. Thank YOU to everyone who has made this possible! If you have pictures of your students working, please share.
Have a great weekend, MCS families!

At the request of Governor Lee, Murfreesboro City Schools will remain closed through April 24. Our CHOW buses will continue to serve breakfast and lunch to children 18 years of age and younger at locations across Murfreesboro. A complete list of CHOW serving locations can be found at www.cityschools.net. SROs are traveling with our CHOW buses and distributing books daily plus tomorrow (Wednesday) they will have school supplies for children.

Parents can also find educational resources, games and read alouds on school and district web pages. Please check out the Little Free Libraries located at schools.

While we have no reason to believe that we have any cases of COVID-19 associated with Murfreesboro City Schools, out of an abundance of caution, MCS will close the week of March 16 through March 20.

Schools will be open during regular school hours on Monday, March 16 for parents of students who have medicine that needs to be retrieved for their children.

Our CHOW buses will begin running next week to help with feeding our students. Information about the CHOW bus schedules will be posted early next week.

ESP will be closed the duration of the week. We apologize for any inconvenience that this closure may cause but we want to ere on the side of caution.

We will continue to monitor the situation and keep staff, parents and our community updated.

post_text: The power of a persuasive letter. Great job Kayla! Erma Siegel Elementary
shared_text:
City of Murfreesboro, TN - Government
February 27 at 8:24 PM ·

Kayla S. Miller read the pledge during the Feb. 27, 2020, meeting of the Murfreesboro City Council. She also met with Mayor Shane McFarland, and sat at the Mayor's desk as part of her invitation to spend time with the Mayor before tonight's City Council meeting.
Earlier this month Kayla Miller, a Siegel Elementary School student, wrote a letter to the Mayor, introducing herself and her desire to be the President of the United States. "I want to be President because I have a passion to be the best I can be for my country," Kayla wrote the Mayor.
Kayla added, "I would love to see what it's like to be in a major roll or political role like mayor."
Kayla got her wish this evening, meeting Mayor McFarland in his office. Congratulations Kayla, you just learned the power of a persuasive letter!

Join us for an amazing night of fun on March 9. The MCs Music Festival performance will take place at 6:00 p.m. at World Outreach Church and includes over 450 students singing in celebration of Music in our Schools Month.

The choir will be accompanied in select songs by the music of Scales Steel de Boro and the Northfield Drumming Ensemble.

Parents and guests are encouraged to arrive by 5:30 p.m. to ensure ample time for seating. World Outreach Church is located at 1921 Hwy 99 (New Salem Highway) in Murfreesboro.

post_text:
February is tree tapping time and when you have a school campus with healthy Maple trees, a lesson plan will probably follow.

Hobgood first graders began their unit of study with a visit from a community partner who introduced the concept of tree tapping. Students learned the science behind Maple syrup through identifying healthy trees, collecting weather data, assembling the correct harvesting equipment and finally making the first taps on the trees this week. And the sap is now flowing!

Next up - making maple syrup and pancakes.

Now, that reminds us of the story "If you give a Pig a Pancake"...she'll want syrup to go with it.

Great job Mr. Ridgely and the first grade team at Hobgood.

Tennessee Department of Education Tennessee STEM Innovation Network City of Murfreesboro, TN - Government Hobgood Elementary

Join the MCS Team - Share the news and let future teachers know.

MCS will host a teacher recruitment fair from 9:30 to 11:30 am on Saturday, February 8 at Scales Elementary School. The fair is designed to match qualified candidates to the available teaching positions for the 2020-21 school year.

Those participating should bring multiple resumes, license documentation and any additional relevant materials to the job fair. Be prepared to interview!

Can't make the job fair....call the MCS Human Resources office.

Additional information about Murfreesboro City Schools can be found on the career page at www.cityschools.net. Scales is located at 2340 St. Andrews Drive in Murfreesboro.

As our day begins, we salute the law enforcement officers who keep us safe, teach character lessons, read with our students, serve as substitute crossing guards, respond to a crisis at the touch of a button, walk our halls, check our doors and genuinely love our students.

We are in awe of you - School Resource Officers, Murfreesboro Police Department and all law enforcement officers. ‪It’s an honor to stop and celebrate National Law Enforcement Day.

text:
As our day begins, we salute the law enforcement officers who keep us safe, teach character lessons, read with our students, serve as substitute crossing guards, respond to a crisis at the touch of a button, walk our halls, check our doors and genuinely love our students.

We are in awe of you - School Resource Officers, Murfreesboro Police Department and all law enforcement officers. ‪It’s an honor to stop and celebrate National Law Enforcement Day.

City of Murfreesboro, TN - Government

post_text:
The Excellence in Education Gala is just around the corner and The City Schools Foundation is thrilled to be honoring former School Board Member, Collier Smith and featuring Discovery School on January 24.

Smith is a community leader who served on the Board of Education from 2011-2018. A founding Trustee and Secretary of The City Schools Foundation, Smith also chaired the first Excellence in Education Gala honoring astronauts Dr. Rhea Seddon and Hoot Gipson in 2007.

Her commitment to our schools has been beyond measure. Join The Foundation on the 24th to celebrate Collier, Discovery and the success of public education in Murfreesboro.

The City Schools Foundation City of Murfreesboro, TN - Government

post_text:
Here is an incredible story that we just had to share about one of our sweet Northfield students.

Maci Lynn’s dad was diagnosed with cancer earlier this year. While he went through surgery and chemotherapy treatments, she remained positive. In September, her dad’s cancer entered remission and Maci Lynn expressed how she wanted to do something for others going through cancer whether it be children or adults.

With the Christmas season approaching, Maci Lynn made 40 goody bags with Christmas food, candy and toiletries to pass out to chemo patients receiving treatments earlier this month. She wrote notes on the bags and passed the goodies out while wishing each patient Merry Christmas.

We are so proud of Maci Lynn and her gifts of kindness. Enjoy the holidays. @murfreesboro.com

post_text:
MCS and John Pittard Elementary are thrilled to announce that Fifth Grade Math and Science Teacher Kyle Cantrell has been named as an Extraordinary Educator by Curriculum Associates. Curriculum Associates named 31 members nationwide to their inaugural class of Extraordinary Educators.

Congratulations Mr. Cantrell on receiving this great honor! So proud you are part of the Pittard Pride.

The 31 selected teachers exhibit best-in-class use of i-Ready and/or Ready in their classroom, illustrate growth and achievement via formal assessments, demonstrate classroom innovation and engagement practices for students, are evangelists for high standards and student achievement, and have been teaching for at least two years. To learn about the 2020 Extraordinary Educators and meet other remarkable teachers like Mr. Cantrell, please visit CurriculumAssociates.com/ExtraordinaryEducators.

City of Murfreesboro, TN - Government Murfreesboro.com
